Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange 

⸻

1. Core Idea
	•	Allows two parties to create a shared secret over an insecure channel
	•	No need to send the actual key

Public data → shared  
Secret values → never shared  
Final key → same on both sides


⸻

2. Problem It Solves
	•	In symmetric encryption:
	•	Key must be shared securely ❌
	•	Diffie-Hellman:
	•	Key is derived, not transmitted ✅

⸻

3. Step-by-Step Process

⸻

Step 0 — Public Agreement

q = prime number  
g = generator  

Example:

q = 29  
g = 3

✔ These are public (anyone can see)

⸻

Step 1 — Alice

Choose secret a = 13  
Compute A = g^a mod q = 3^13 mod 29 = 19  
Send A to Bob


⸻

Step 2 — Bob

Choose secret b = 15  
Compute B = g^b mod q = 3^15 mod 29 = 26  
Send B to Alice


⸻

Step 3 — Shared Key Calculation

Alice computes:

Key = B^a mod q = 26^13 mod 29 = 10

Bob computes:

Key = A^b mod q = 19^15 mod 29 = 10

✔ Both get same key = 10

⸻

4. Why It Works

(g^a)^b mod q = (g^b)^a mod q

👉 Same result on both sides

⸻

5. What Attacker Sees

q, g, A, B

But cannot compute:

a or b → therefore cannot get key


⸻

6. Security Basis
	•	Hard problem:

Discrete Logarithm Problem

	•	Easy:

g^a mod q

	•	Hard:

Find a from result


⸻

7. Real-World Parameters
	•	q size:
	•	2048 bits or more
	•	Very large → infeasible to break

⸻

8. OpenSSL Commands

Generate parameters

openssl dhparam -out dhparams.pem 2048


⸻

View parameters

openssl dhparam -in dhparams.pem -text -noout


⸻

Output includes:

P → prime number (q)  
G → generator


⸻

9. Major Weakness (IMPORTANT)

Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) Attack
	•	Attacker intercepts communication
	•	Pretends to be:
	•	Bob to Alice
	•	Alice to Bob

Alice ↔ Attacker ↔ Bob

✔ Both think they are communicating securely
❌ Actually attacker controls keys

⸻

10. Why MITM Works
	•	No authentication in basic Diffie-Hellman
	•	No identity verification

⸻

11. Real-World Fix
	•	Use with:
	•	Digital signatures
	•	Certificates (TLS)

⸻

12. Key Takeaways
	•	Diffie-Hellman = key exchange, not encryption
	•	Works over insecure channels
	•	Shared secret is never transmitted
	•	Vulnerable to MITM without authentication

⸻

13. One-line Summary

Diffie-Hellman allows two parties to generate a shared secret over an insecure channel using public values and private secrets, but requires authentication to prevent MITM attacks.